I found the indifferent reaction from another woman really powerful because sure in this little bubble of reality called fan twitter everyone is like 'own your trauma' but out in the real world? That shit happens. Women can be the worst for minimising other women's pain.

Starlight is a perfect example. Bad shit happens, she is coerced by a man in a position of assumed power over her. Her reaction is real and visceral. A lot of people are negative about this part of the story but the story shows it for a purpose.

Sometimes you won't enjoy the show as much as feel the show. That's it's whole fucking bag. If we sterilise media to not include reality then we actually make it harder for people to realise how despicable and unacceptable some things are.

feel fleeting empathy for and hate yourself for it. There's not a single 'morally good' person in the show. No, not even Hughie. That is probably what makes it resonate so much, there are no heroes. This is down and dirty hyperrealism.

then you need to switch it off. It's a world where innocents are murdered, where people are sexually assaulted, where children are drugged and used as weapons and so poorly socialised that they become monsters. There's nazis adored by the public. There's terrible people you will

And to clarify, I say character throughout because this doesn't work with real people. Real people's identities belong to them. Fictional people's identities belong to everyone.

So I don't actually care what the 'facts' are about a character. The choice is to a) stick with the read that does nothing at best or harms at worst, or b) support the read that uplifts a minority, even of you don't share it.
On the other hand, insisting a character is heterosexual does have an impact, because it removes queer narratives and the tiny bit of visibility we try and eek out for ourselves.

No straight person will be harmed by saying 'this character is queer', because heterosexuality is the societal default. If you're straight, congrats, your sexuality is reinforced by pretty much every piece of media out there.

I do think JA is trying to do better, albeit he's a WIP. I think JP wants to sound better but isn't really trying to do better. I don't think either of them fully empathise with queer fans or realise their power. I still think JA might get it at some point. JP never will.

MC is the kid who sees a toybox and gleefully empties it so he can hand out the toys to all the other kids and get everyone playing together.

JP, I suspect, is the kid who upends the toybox looking for the toy he wants but without thought for whether other toys might get damaged

JP on the other hand has pissed me off. You may have read my thoughts on JA and MC's treatment of their characters through the lens of childhood and engagement with play. Tl;dr, JA is the kid with 1 special toy that never leaves his side. He'll share anything but that.

JA could have done better. I suspect that not rocking the boat is part of getting past the prequel unpleasantness. I'm disappointed in him appearing to speak over Misha with his interpretation but honestly I think much of that relates to his possessiveness of Dean and Dean's POV.

It's not the words, it's the delivery. It's the implied 'but not where I can see it'. My dad would not tell his wife about my last 2 relationships because they were queer. Me being queer was okay to him but still something that couldn't be discussed. So yes, this all hit home.

JP's part of the answer, brushing past the fact that it wasn't requested, was reminiscent of my own experiences of low-key homophobia. The rant that ends with 'love whoever the fuck you want!' has that same undertow of aggression that I've had from people in my rl.
I have no reason to believe that's the case, and the body language doesn't seem to hold up to JP being any kind of 'saviour' in this situation, except perhaps in his own mind.

Now JP's answer, even just him deciding to wade  vociferously into a question he wasn't part of, is a whole other story. The only justification I could think up for it was that JA had asked him to take over when the q came up because he was anxious of not fucking up.

That an angel could love in a 'human' way. Yes I do think there's bleed through there with his own beliefs and POV, but Dean/him not being able to comprehend it is not the same as him saying it doesn't exist.

@redbrickrose I think that's honestly the thing. And it's hard to see it as anything but poor when what you want is the antethesis of what you got. But for the people looking for that linear narrative, the fact that it had a beginning that matched the end is enough to make it good.

@redbrickrose Now for those of us looking for non linear, decentralised narratives, anything BUT bronly is more appealing to us.

@redbrickrose My conclusion is that people like different types of stories. One type leans you towards bronly, and this seems to be the people who like the traditional hero narrative with 'just deserves' at the end. The others are less into linear narrative and want it to branch and continue.

Truthfully, idk if there are higher beings. But I don't really want to piss any off just in case. So whenever I'm doing fandom stuff I'll use enochian glyphs as a substitution cipher. Less chance of me summoning an actual demon that way.

Keeping the 'essential' part of each glyph, I would propose

VAMEGON AUVAMEOR GON

In both cases this would be written as https://t.co/rNqzfW8D24

with the full substitution of 'I love you' being

VAN MED GON GRAUPHA VAN MED ORH GON.

This approach is very literal, and more suited to written than spoken language. That's where Ceremonial magic comes in, as transformation in service of the aesthetic is encouraged.

This system has been used in alchemy and ceremonial magic to keep secrets away from the uninitiated. Various ciphers can be used, but let's keep it simple and go with direct substitution. 

Evol breaks down to (phonetic pronunciation of the enochian letters)
Graupha Van Med Ourh,
Moving to the use of the Enochian as a substitution language,  we can translate the word for love directly. The enochian alphabet is made of glyphs, each with an associated sound.

Thee in Enochian is yls. So if we accept 'worship' in place of love, the phrase would be

YLS HOARTH OL 

As Enochian reads right to left.

But it's not generically 'I love you'. It doesn't appear that 'love' has a given translation in Enochian. To get closer to 'I love you', then ol is correct for 'I' and 'you' is gi. However, given the c16th origin of Enochian, the more intimate 'I love thee' fits better IMO.

First up, the phrase we use in spn fandom as 'I love you' - Olani hoath ol - doesn't literally mean that. It directly translates to 'I worship two men'. If we assume the two men are the speaker and his subject, then it's basically  a, cough, homosexual declaration of devotion.
So I've been on a bit of a deep dive into Enochian and it's use as a both a standalone language (Angelic) and as a substitution alphabet (alchemy/ceremonial) and I have learned some things.
